From e674915552cb1bd46c1a1643d1a400cf7f868910 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VyOS LS1046A maintainers <ask20@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: Thu, 14 May 2026 02:34:50 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fman: add Parse/Classify/Distribute (PCD) orchestration
 subsystem
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The FMan PCD complex (Parser/KeyGen/Classifier/Manipulator/Policer/
Replicator, NXP LS1046A Reference Manual chapter 8 §8.7–8.10) is the
hardware programmer interface that lets a consumer install exact-match
flow rules at line rate. Mainline 6.18 ships only the parser+RSS
subset (fman_keygen.c default-scheme path); the exact-match path that
ASK2's ask.ko needs (see specs/ask2-rewrite-spec.md v1.0 §13.3) is not
covered by any existing in-tree driver.

This patch is PR14a — the orchestration-only scaffolding step of a
multi-part series (PR14a..PR14g per plans/ASK2-IMPLEMENTATION.md).
It introduces:

  - struct fman_pcd, the per-FMan PCD state container, allocated and
    released via a single owner (fman_pcd_init / fman_pcd_release).
    Carries a 96 KiB MURAM budget (FMAN_PCD_MURAM_RESERVED_BYTES) and
    six list-heads (kg/cc/manip/plcr/replic + a generic resource list)
    that PR14b–PR14f will attach per-engine state objects to.
  - A new pointer slot, struct fman.pcd, populated by fman_probe()
    immediately after dev_set_drvdata() via
    devm_add_action_or_reset(fman_pcd_release_action) so the release
    runs at the right point in the unwind even if probe later fails.
  - Three public accessors that ask.ko consumes:
        struct fman_pcd *fman_get_pcd(struct fman *);
        struct device   *fman_get_dev(struct fman *);
        u8               fman_get_id(struct fman *);
    All EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL.
  - One public budget accessor:
        size_t fman_pcd_get_muram_budget(struct fman_pcd *);
    Also EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL.
  - Seven internal helpers (fman_pcd_muram_alloc/free,
    fman_pcd_get_{fman,lock,kg_list,cc_list,manip_list,plcr_list,
    replic_list}) declared in a private header
    drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd_internal.h. These
    are *not* EXPORT_SYMBOL'd — they are intra-module symbols within
    fsl_dpaa_fman.ko so PR14b–PR14f siblings (which live in the same
    module) can use them without exposing them across the kernel.
  - A debugfs node /sys/kernel/debug/fman_pcd/<id>/muram_budget that
    reports remaining MURAM bytes (read-only, ASCII decimal).
  - Public header include/linux/fsl/fman_pcd.h carrying forward
    declarations for KG/CC/manip/plcr/replic handles (filled in by
    PR14b–PR14f) and FMAN_PCD_API_VERSION = 1.
  - Kconfig FSL_FMAN_PCD, bool, default y, gated on FSL_FMAN.

What this patch does NOT do
---------------------------
No FMan hardware register is touched. No KeyGen/Classifier scheme is
programmed. No MURAM region is claimed beyond the bookkeeping budget
itself. fman_pcd_muram_alloc() forwards to fman_muram_alloc() inside
the reserved budget; it is the future PR14b–PR14f code paths that
actually call it.

Provenance (v1.1)
---------------------
The file headers cite LS1046A RM §8.7–8.10 and the in-tree
fman_keygen.c/fman_port.c register layouts as the only authoritative
references. No code from the legacy NXP SDK fm_pcd_*.c tree was read
during authoring; this is the "Option C-modernize" path agreed on in
specs/ask2-rewrite-spec.md §16 (risk #12) and approved in commit
07d5a96.

Build / link validation
-----------------------
ARCH=arm64 defconfig + FSL_FMAN_PCD=y, native compile on aarch64
Cobalt 100 (Ampere Altra). make Image, zero warnings. The four
public symbols appear in System.map with __ksymtab entries:

  $ grep -E '__ksymtab_(fman_get_pcd|fman_pcd_(init|release|get_muram_budget))' System.map
  ffff800081dfb3d0 r __ksymtab_fman_get_pcd
  ffff800081dfb3dc r __ksymtab_fman_pcd_get_muram_budget
  ffff800081dfb3e8 r __ksymtab_fman_pcd_init
  ffff800081dfb3f4 r __ksymtab_fman_pcd_release

The seven internal helpers are present as T-symbols with no ksymtab
entry, as expected for intra-module use.

Runtime validation deferred to a follow-up commit on the same PR14a
patch series (TFTP boot on Mono Gateway DK + dmesg banner check +
debugfs muram_budget read). PR14b is the first patch that programs
FMan silicon registers.

